observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed that:
a.	The Inventory Committee prepare and submit the CY 2023 RPCPPE immediately, and henceforth ensure the timely preparation and submission of the annual RPCPPE;




b.	The Accounting Office and the Inventory Committee reconcile the PPE balances between the RPCPPE and the FS, and the Municipal Accountant present the correct balances in the FS;





c.	The Accounting Office provide complete and correct details of the current and future PPE acquisitions for reference in the computation of depreciation;

d.	The Inventory Committee exhaust all efforts to retrieve records/information pertaining to PPEs with no details so that the Accounting Office can provide the corresponding depreciation expenses of the remaining undepreciated PPE; and

e.	The Management conduct one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with the guidelines and procedures outlined under COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended and:

a.	The Accounting Office and the Inventory Committee agreed to reconcile the PPE balances between the RPCPPE and the FS, and the Municipal Accountant present the correct balances in the FS;



b. The Municipal Accountant agreed to make necessary adjusting entries for the balances of disposed PPE still included in the books amounting to ₱0.942 million;

c.	The Management agreed to expedite the disposal of the remaining unserviceable properties to prevent further deterioration and to realize income therefrom if found to be saleable;


d. TheInventory Committee agreed to exhaust all efforts to retrieve records/information pertaining to PPEs with no details so that the Accounting Office can provide the corresponding depreciation expenses of the remaining undepreciated PPE; and


e. The Inventory Management agreed to effect the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with the guidelines and procedures prescribed under COA
Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended and the Management agreed that:
The Inventory Committee prepare and submit the CY 2023 RPCPPE immediately, and henceforth ensure the timely preparation and submission of the annual RPCPPE;
The Accounting Office and the Inventory Committee reconcile the PPE balances between the RPCPPE and the FS, and the Municipal Accountant present the correct balances in the FS;
The Accounting Office provide complete and correct details of the current and future PPE acquisitions for reference in the computation of depreciation;
The Inventory Committee exhaust all efforts to retrieve records/information pertaining to PPEs with no details so that the Accounting Office can provide the corresponding depreciation expenses of the remaining undepreciated PPE; and
The Management conduct one-time cleansing of PPE accounts in accordance with the guidelines and procedures outlined under COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
Verify/check the amounts in liquidation reports submitted to the Provincial Accountant of fund transfers with discrepancies in the balance recorded in the books of the Province;
Determine/confirm the status of  fund transfers  recorded and included in the Due to LGUs account of the Municipality but were booked up by the Province as an expense, and prepare adjusting entries, if necessary, to correct the account balances;
Cause the reconciliation of the inter-agency payable account Due to LGUs of  the Municipality with that of the reciprocal receivable account Due from LGUs of the Province, and effect the necessary adjusting entries on the variance noted to reflect the correct balances of  said accounts; and
Conduct a periodic reconciliation of inter-agency reciprocal accounts to ensure accurate balances of payable/receivable accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:

a.	Verify/ check the amounts in liquidation reports submitted to the Provincial Accountant of fund transfers with discrepancies in the balance recorded in the books of the Province;

b. Determine/ confirm the status of fund transfers recorded and included in the Due to LGUs account of the Municipality but were booked up by the Province as an expense, and prepare adjusting entries, if necessary, to correct the account balances; 

c. Cause the reconciliation of the inter-agency payable account Due to LGUs of the Municipality with that of the reciprocal receivable account Due from LGUs of the Province, and effect the necessary adjusting entries on the variance noted to reflect the correct balances of said accounts; and

d.	Conduct a periodic reconciliation of inter-agency reciprocal accounts to ensure accurate balances of payable/ receivable accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that Management:

1.	Issue Demand Letters to the following:

a)	previous collector and disbursing officers with unsettled accountabilities;

b)	recipients of grants for livelihood capital for the settlement or liquidation of their accounts; and

c)	employees and suppliers/ creditors with over claimed payments;

2.	Require the Municipal Accountant to: 

a)	verify details / reconcile / adjust the various other receivables under the Trust Fund books;

b)	regularly conduct monitoring and analysis of Other Receivables; and

c)	provide Allowance for Impairment to dormant Other Receivables and subsequently request for write-off, if warranted.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
Verify/check the amounts in liquidation reports submitted to the Provincial Accountant of fund transfers with discrepancies in the balance recorded in the books of the Province;
Determine/confirm the status of  fund transfers  recorded and included in the Due to LGUs account of the Municipality but were booked up by the Province as an expense, and prepare adjusting entries, if necessary, to correct the account balances;
Cause the reconciliation of the inter-agency payable account Due to LGUs of  the Municipality with that of the reciprocal receivable account Due from LGUs of the Province, and effect the necessary adjusting entries on the variance noted to reflect the correct balances of  said accounts; and
Conduct a periodic reconciliation of inter-agency reciprocal accounts to ensure accurate balances of payable/receivable accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:

a.	continuously provide the Provincial Accountant the data on the Province’s share in the real property and other tax collections made by the Municipality and ensure reconciliation of the balances at year-end;

b.	provide the Provincial Accountant the details of the recorded balances of fund transfers recorded in CY 2016 and prior year; 

c.	submit liquidation reports to the Province for fund transfers with projects/programs already implemented/completed; and

d.	verify liquidation reports already submitted to the Province and  ensure recording in the books by requesting a copy of the Journal Entry Voucher from the Provincial Accountant.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
a. continuously provide the Provincial Accountant the data on the Province’s share in the real property and other tax collections made by the Municipality and ensure reconciliation of the balances at year-end;
b. provide the Provincial Accountant the details of the recorded balances of fund transfers recorded in CY 2016 and prior year;
c. submit liquidation reports to the Province for fund transfers with projects/programs already implemented/completed; and
d. verify liquidation reports already submitted to the Province and ensure recording in the books by requesting a copy of the Journal Entry Voucher from the Provincial Accountant.

We recommended and Management agreed that:

a.	the Municipal Accountant regularly provide the Provincial Accountant with data on the Province’s share in the real property and other tax collections made by the Municipality;

b.	the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer remit the valid current due Province’s share in real property and other taxes which remained unremitted by the Municipality;

c.	the Municipal Accountant trace the details of the fund transfers by requesting copies of JEVs of the Province; 


d. the Municipal Accountant submit liquidation documents for fund transfers recorded by the Province as receivable from the Municipality; and


e. the Municipal Planning and Development Officer and the Municipal Engineer evaluate the two (2) unimplemented projects, if still feasible, and expedite their implementation.

We recommended and Management agreed that:

a.	the implementing offices expedite the completion of the on-going development projects, namely: 1) Development of Sibunag Sports Arena, 2) Concreting of Municipal Road, 3) Support to Barangay projects, and 4) Repair/Improvement of various Barangay roads;

b.	the Municipal Development Council ensure that the development projects identified in the ADP are feasible and can be implemented within the year with the proposed budget allocation;


c. the implementation of the development projects is within the time schedule as targeted in the ADP and optimally utilize the 20% Development Fund; and



d. the Municipal Engineer and Municipal Accountant ensure and cause the submission of complete supporting documents for disbursements on infrastructure projects.

We recommended and Management agreed that:

a.	the mandatory 1% IRA for MCPC be allocated for an effective and efficient   implementation of the council’s programs/projects/activities;

b.	the objectives and activities along with expected results focusing on child friendly programs, projects and services be included in the MCPC Plan and Budget for next year;

c.	intervention and diversion program for the children and youth be provided  based on statistical data; and

d.	results of implemented PPAs be appropriately measured and a report thereon be submitted to the concerned Offices including COA Audit Team for proper evaluation.

We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
a.	regularly provide the Provincial Accountant with data on the Province’s share in the real property and other tax collections made by the Municipality;

b.	remit the valid current due Province’s share in real property and other taxes which remained unremitted by the Municipality;
c.	trace the details of the fund transfers by requesting copies of JEVs of the Province;
d.	submit liquidation documents for fund transfers recorded by the Province as Due from LGUs; and
e.	conduct periodic reconciliation with the Provincial Accountant.

We recommended and the Municipal Development Council through the Municipal Planning and Development Officer agreed to ensure that:

a.	the utilization of the 20% Development Fund be optimally utilized;

b.	projects identified in the plan are feasible and with complete documentation;

c.	projects are properly scheduled and can be implemented within the year with the proposed budget allocation; and

d.	projects which are discontinued or abandoned such as the Improvement of School Building are declared savings and utilized in accordance with the guidelines and procedures in LBC No. 112 dated  June 10, 2016.
